Citation.sTitle: Relative Permittivity Measurements of Gaseous, Liquid, and Supercritical Dimethyl Ether
Citation.sAbstract: The relative permittivity ( r) of dimethyl ether (DME) was measured as a function of temperature and pressure  in the gaseous, liquid, and supercritical states. The temperature and pressure ranges studied were (303 to 403) K  and (0.04 to 33.2) MPa, respectively. The relative permittivity was fitted to the reduced density (Fr) using the  function ( r - 1)/(2 r + 1), and the apparent dipole moment (i*) of the liquid phase was calculated using Kirkwood s  theory of molecular polarizability.
